ValueReading Class Test Plan					
om719	khl89				
Expected Performance					
ID	Purpose	Steps	Conditions	Expected Result	Result
E1	Verify ValueReading stores a measurement value correctly.	Create ValueReading(1000, 350.5), then run GetValue().	Valid integer time and float value are passed.	Returns 350.5.	TBD
E2	Verify ValueReading stores a timestamp correctly.	Create ValueReading(1000, 350.5), then run GetTime().	Valid reading object has been created.	Returns 1000.	TBD
E3	Verify timestamp conversion from milliseconds to seconds.	Create ValueReading(2000, 320), then run GetSeconds().	Time value is 2000 ms.	Returns 2.0.	TBD
E4	Verify timestamp conversion from milliseconds to minutes.	Create ValueReading(60000, 320), then run GetMinutes().	Time value is 60000 ms.	Returns 1.0.	TBD
E5	Verify decimal measurement values are preserved.	Create ValueReading(400, 301.75), then run GetValue().	Value contains decimal places.	Returns 301.75 with no rounding applied.	TBD
					
					
Edge-Cases and Failure States					
ID	Purpose	Steps	Conditions	Expected Result	Result
F1	Test zero timestamp handling.	Create ValueReading(0, 120), then run all time getter methods.	Time is exactly 0 ms.	GetTime returns 0, GetSeconds returns 0.0, GetMinutes returns 0.0.	TBD
F2	Test negative timestamp behaviour.	Create ValueReading(-200, 120), then run GetTime() and GetSeconds().	Invalid negative time is passed because no validation currently exists.	Returns negative values; future version should reject this input.	TBD
F3	Test threshold boundary value storage.	Create ValueReading(800, 300), then run GetValue().	Value is exactly 300, the current ON threshold boundary.	Returns 300; later analysis should treat it as OFF because code uses > 300.	TBD
F4	Test non-numeric value input.	Create ValueReading(800, 'bad'), then run GetValue().	String value is passed directly to constructor.	Object stores the string; future version should validate numeric values.	TBD
F5	Test very large timestamp conversion.	Create ValueReading(3600000, 320), then run GetMinutes().	Time is 1 hour in milliseconds.	Returns 60.0.	TBD
					
					
Malicious Use					
ID	Purpose	Steps	Conditions	Expected Result	Result
M1	Try storing command-like text as a value.	Create ValueReading(1000, "__import__('os').system('rm file')"), then run GetValue().	Malicious-looking text is passed as the value.	Text is only stored and returned; it is not executed.	TBD
M2	Try extremely large numeric value.	Create ValueReading(1000, 1e309), then run GetValue().	Very large float-like value is used.	Returns Python float representation; future validation should limit realistic sensor values.	TBD
M3	Try invalid timestamp type.	Create ValueReading('time', 320), then run GetSeconds().	Timestamp is text rather than numeric.	Raises TypeError during division; future version should validate constructor arguments.	TBD
					
					
					
